#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:284
msgid ":keyword:`!match` Statements"
msgstr ":keyword:`!match` У»ГтЈЦ"

#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:286
msgid ""
"A :keyword:`match` statement takes an expression and compares its value to "
"successive patterns given as one or more case blocks.  This is superficially"
" similar to a switch statement in C, Java or JavaScript (and many other "
"languages), but it's more similar to pattern matching in languages like Rust"
" or Haskell. Only the first pattern that matches gets executed and it can "
"also extract components (sequence elements or object attributes) from the "
"value into variables. If no case matches, none of the branches is executed."
msgstr ""
":keyword:`match` У»ГтЈЦТјЦтЈЌСИђСИфУАеУЙЙт╝Јт╣ХТііт«Ѓуџётђ╝СИјСИђСИфТѕќтцџСИф case тЮЌу╗ЎтЄ║уџёСИђу│╗тѕЌТеАт╝ЈУ┐ЏУАїТ»ћУЙЃсђѓУ┐ЎУАежЮбСИітЃЈ CсђЂJava Тѕќ "
"JavaScript№╝ѕС╗ЦтЈіУ«ИтцџтЁХС╗ќуеІт║ЈУ«ЙУ«АУ»ГУеђ№╝ЅСИГуџё switch У»ГтЈЦ№╝їСйєтЁХт«ът«ЃТЏ┤тЃЈ Rust Тѕќ Haskell "
"СИГуџёТеАт╝Јтї╣жЁЇсђѓтЈфТюЅуггСИђСИфтї╣жЁЇуџёТеАт╝ЈС╝џУбФТЅДУАї№╝їт╣ХСИћт«ЃУ┐ўтЈ»С╗ЦТЈљтЈќтђ╝уџёу╗ёТѕљжЃетѕє№╝ѕт║ЈтѕЌуџётЁЃу┤аТѕќт»╣У▒Ауџёт▒ъТђД№╝ЅУхІу╗ЎтЈўжЄЈсђѓтдѓТъюТ▓АТюЅтї╣жЁЇуџёcase№╝їтѕЎСИЇТЅДУАїС╗╗СйЋтѕєТћ»сђѓ"

#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:295
msgid ""
"The simplest form compares a subject value against one or more literals::"
msgstr "Тюђу«ђтЇЋуџётйбт╝ЈТў»т░єСИђСИфСИ╗У»Гтђ╝СИјСИђСИфТѕќтцџСИфтГЌжЮбтђ╝У┐ЏУАїТ»ћУЙЃ№╝џ"

#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:297
msgid ""
"def http_error(status):\n"
"    match status:\n"
"        case 400:\n"
"            return \"Bad request\"\n"
"        case 404:\n"
"            return \"Not found\"\n"
"        case 418:\n"
"            return \"I'm a teapot\"\n"
"        case _:\n"
"            return \"Something's wrong with the internet\""
msgstr ""
"def http_error(status):\n"
"    match status:\n"
"        case 400:\n"
"            return \"Bad request\"\n"
"        case 404:\n"
"            return \"Not found\"\n"
"        case 418:\n"
"            return \"I'm a teapot\"\n"
"        case _:\n"
"            return \"Something's wrong with the internet\""

#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:308
msgid ""
"Note the last block: the \"variable name\" ``_`` acts as a *wildcard* and "
"never fails to match."
msgstr "Т│еТёЈТюђтљјСИђСИфС╗БуаЂтЮЌ№╝џРђютЈўжЄЈтљЇРђЮ ``_`` УбФСйюСИ║ *жђџжЁЇугд* т╣Хт┐Ёт«џС╝џтї╣жЁЇТѕљтіЪсђѓ"

#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:311
msgid ""
"You can combine several literals in a single pattern using ``|`` (\"or\")::"
msgstr "СйатЈ»С╗Цуће ``|`` №╝ѕРђюТѕќРђЮ№╝Ѕт░єтцџСИфтГЌжЮбтђ╝у╗ётљѕтѕ░СИђСИфТеАт╝ЈСИГ№╝џ"

#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:313
msgid ""
"case 401 | 403 | 404:\n"
"    return \"Not allowed\""
msgstr ""
"case 401 | 403 | 404:\n"
"    return \"Not allowed\""

#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:316
msgid ""
"Patterns can look like unpacking assignments, and can be used to bind "
"variables::"
msgstr "тйбтдѓУДБтїЁУхІтђ╝уџёТеАт╝ЈтЈ»УбФућеС║ју╗Љт«џтЈўжЄЈ№╝џ"

#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:319
msgid ""
"# point is an (x, y) tuple\n"
"match point:\n"
"    case (0, 0):\n"
"        print(\"Origin\")\n"
"    case (0, y):\n"
"        print(f\"Y={y}\")\n"
"    case (x, 0):\n"
"        print(f\"X={x}\")\n"
"    case (x, y):\n"
"        print(f\"X={x}, Y={y}\")\n"
"    case _:\n"
"        raise ValueError(\"Not a point\")"
msgstr ""
"# point Тў»СИђСИф (x, y) тЁЃу╗ё\n"
"match point:\n"
"    case (0, 0):\n"
"        print(\"Origin\")\n"
"    case (0, y):\n"
"        print(f\"Y={y}\")\n"
"    case (x, 0):\n"
"        print(f\"X={x}\")\n"
"    case (x, y):\n"
"        print(f\"X={x}, Y={y}\")\n"
"    case _:\n"
"        raise ValueError(\"Not a point\")"

#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:332
msgid ""
"Study that one carefully!  The first pattern has two literals, and can be "
"thought of as an extension of the literal pattern shown above.  But the next"
" two patterns combine a literal and a variable, and the variable *binds* a "
"value from the subject (``point``).  The fourth pattern captures two values,"
" which makes it conceptually similar to the unpacking assignment ``(x, y) = "
"point``."
msgstr ""
"У»иС╗ћу╗єтГдС╣аТГцС╗БуаЂ№╝ЂуггСИђСИфТеАт╝ЈТюЅСИцСИфтГЌжЮбтђ╝№╝їтЈ»УДєСИ║тЅЇУ┐░тГЌжЮбтђ╝ТеАт╝ЈуџёТЅЕт▒ЋсђѓТјЦСИІТЮЦуџёСИцСИфТеАт╝Ју╗ЊтљѕС║єСИђСИфтГЌжЮбтђ╝тњїСИђСИфтЈўжЄЈ№╝їтЈўжЄЈ *у╗Љт«џ* "
"С║єТЮЦУЄфСИ╗У»Г№╝ѕ``point``№╝ЅуџёСИђСИфтђ╝сђѓуггтЏЏСИфТеАт╝ЈТЇЋУјиС║єСИцСИфтђ╝№╝їСй┐тЁХтюеТдѓт┐хСИіСИјУДБтїЁУхІтђ╝ ``(x, y) = point`` у▒╗С╝╝сђѓ"

#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:339
msgid ""
"If you are using classes to structure your data you can use the class name "
"followed by an argument list resembling a constructor, but with the ability "
"to capture attributes into variables::"
msgstr "тдѓТъюућеу▒╗у╗ёу╗ЄТЋ░ТЇ«№╝їтЈ»С╗ЦућеРђюу▒╗тљЇтљјТјЦСИђСИфтЈѓТЋ░тѕЌУАеРђЮУ┐ЎуДЇтЙѕтЃЈТъёжђатЎеуџётйбт╝Ј№╝їТііт▒ъТђДТЇЋУјитѕ░тЈўжЄЈжЄї№╝џ"

#: ../../tutorial/controlflow.rst:343
msgid ""
"class Point:\n"
"    def __init__(self, x, y):\n"
"        self.x = x\n"
"        self.y = y\n"
"\n"
"def where_is(point):\n"
"    match point:\n"
"        case Point(x=0, y=0):\n"
"            print(\"Origin\")\n"
"        case Point(x=0, y=y):\n"
"            print(f\"Y={y}\")\n"
"        case Point(x=x, y=0):\n"
"            print(f\"X={x}\")\n"
"        case Point():\n"
"            print(\"Somewhere else\")\n"
"        case _:\n"
"            print(\"Not a point\")"
msgstr ""
"class Point:\n"
"    def __init__(self, x, y):\n"
